  <h1 id="start">Start</h1>
  <h2>Dependencies</h2>
  <p>
    To work with Manuskript, you need to install <a href="http://rvm.io/">Ruby</a> and <a href="https://github.com/middleman/middleman/blob/master/README.md">Middleman</a>). This can be a pain in the ass if you’re unexperienced — pull through and let the nice people on the interweb help out.
  </p>
  <h2>Download</h2>
  <p>Fork or download Manuskript at <a href="https://github.com/opoloo/manuskript">GitHub</a>.</p>

  <p>After downloading, the project’s folder structure looks like this:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>config — <em>for the deployment magic</em> — don’t touch that</li>
    <li>docs — <em>where you document your project, to be build with <a href="http://www.mkdocs.org/">MkDocs</a></em> — touch if you want</li>
    <li>locales — <em>for multi-language support</em> — touch if you have more than one language in your project</li>
    <li>source — <em>where you put the real content of your website</em> — touch. Definitely.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>The rest of the files are needed to build a deploy (a running version) of the project. They have various, boring dependencies. Ignore those for now.</p>

  <h2>Start local server</h2>
  <p>To work on your website, open your terminal, go into your project’s directory, and start a local server with the command <code>middleman server</code></p>
  <p>This will start the server and generate a link to your project, like <a href"http://localhost.localdomain:4567">http://localhost.localdomain:4567</a>. Copy this URL into your browser to have a preview of your project.</p>
  <p>You’re all set up. Now let’s <a href="content.html">add some content</a> to you first site.</p>
